The only way for the degree of a product to drop below 7 would be to cancel two polynomials together, which would cause the degree to drop by 1. However, the product can have a degree of at least 7. This happens if the 7th degree terms of $p(t)$ and $q(t)$ are not canceled away but instead are combined.
Therefore, the highest power appearing in $p(t)\cdot q(t)$ is 7, so we can conclude that the degree of $p(t)\cdot q(t)$ is $\boxed{7}.$

Since both $p(t)$ and $q(t)$ are polynomials, $p(t)\cdot q(t)$ will also be a polynomial.  To find the degree of this polynomial, we can look at the highest degree parts of both $p(t)$ and $q(t)$.
### BREAKDOWN
• $p(t)$ has the highest degree term $\ldots + a_7t^7$
• $q(t)$ has the highest degree term $\ldots + b_7t^7$
• Then, the highest degree term of $p(t)\cdot q(t)$ is $(\ldots + a_7t^7)(\ldots + b_7t^7) = \ldots + a_7b_7t^{7+7} = \ldots + a_7b_7t^{14}$
### Therefore, 
$p(t)\cdot q(t)$ has the highest degree term $\ldots + a_7b_7t^{14}$ so it is a sixteenth-degree polynomial.  It also has fifteen other terms that are just combinations of lower degree terms from $p(t)$ and $q(t)$.

The exponents $m_i$ are between 0 and 6, inclusive, and the exponents $n_j$ are also between 0 and 6, inclusive.
We multiply the two polynomials to obtain $p(t)\cdot q(t)$:\begin{align*} p(t)\cdot q(t)&=a(t-t_1)^{m_1}\dots (t-t_7)^{m_7}c(t-t_8)^{n_1}\dots (t-t_{14})^{n_7}\\ &=ac(t-t_1)^{m_1}\dots (t-t_7)^{m_7}(t-t_8)^{n_1}\dots (t-t_{14})^{n_7}\\ &=ac(t^{14} - t_{1}t^{13}-\dots-t_{14}^{n_7})\dots\\ &=ac(t^{14}+t^{13}+\dots+t^{7})^{7}.\end{align*}Since the sum of the 7 highest powers in the binomial expansion of $(t^{14}+t^{13}+\dots+t^{7})^{7}$ is 7, we see that the polynomial $p(t)\cdot q(t)$ is an $\boxed{14th}$ degree polynomial.
